\par }{\b\fs24\cf13 New Kits for Demi-Rangers
\par }{\fs24 
\par \~\~\tab Just as you're free to create new ranger kits, it's also possible to design kits specifically for demi-rangers. Follow the suggestions outlined in the Creating New Kits section above. The DM has the right to disallow }{\i\fs24 any}{\fs24 
 kit he feels is inappropriate for his campaign.
\par \~\~\tab Some suggestions for demi-ranger kits:
\par \~\~\tab }{\b\fs24 Dwarven Spelunker.}{\fs24  This is a subterranean ranger whose primary terrain encompasses caves and underground passages.
\par \~\~\tab }{\b\fs24 Gnomish Terraformer.}{\fs24  He pursues techniques for physically reshaping the lay of the land.
\par \~\~\tab }{\b\fs24 Halfling Agronomist.}{\fs24  He's a master of agriculture and animal husbandry.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13 Dual-Classed Rangers
\par }{\fs24 
\par \~\~\tab Dual-classed characters must be human. A dual class ranger may be of any character kit, presuming the DM allows it in his campaign.
\par \~\~\tab To change from a ranger to another class, the ranger must have a minimum score of 15 in Strength, Dexterity, and Wisdom. He must have a score of 17 or better in the prime requisites of the new class.
\par \~\~\tab If a character from another class wants to switch to a ranger, he must have a minimum score of 15 in his prime requisites and a score of 17 or better in Strength, Dexterity, and Wisdom.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24\cf13 Multi-Class Rangers
\par }{\fs24 
\par    \tab The main multi-class option open for a ranger is the half-elf cleric/ranger. The half-elf advances in both classes simultaneously, up to 16th level ranger and 14th level cleric. All the usual rules for multi-class characters as given in the }{
\i\fs24 Player's Handbook}{\fs24  should be followed.
\par 
\par }{\b\fs24 Optional Rule: The Ranger-Druid
\par }{\fs24 \~\~\tab Generally, a ranger/druid combination is not possible, due to the conflicting alignments of the classes. However, campaign conditions may allow their creation, should the players and DM decide that they wish to experiment with them.

\par \~\~\tab First, there must be a nature deity of good alignment whose specialty priests are druidic. Second, the priesthood must have an allied group of rangers. Given these conditions, a half-elf ranger/druid character may be possible.
\par \~\~\tab Such a character is still bound by racial level limits, in this case 16th level ranger and 9th 
level druid. Even if the optional level advancement for exceptional ability scores is used, such a character is unlikely to become a 12th level druid (a level for which the character must fight). At the very least, the character will have formidable enemi
e
s among conservative members of the priestly hierarchy, and is likely to become the target of subtle plots. Also, such a character would be under constant pressure from divided loyalties, as his chosen professions will tend to pull him in different direct
ions.
\par }{\b\fs32\cf13 
